{"questionId":"22579244","questionHtml":"<p>By deleting <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>, use Prim’s algorithm starting at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> to find a lower bound for the length of the inspector’s journey.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt to form MST without vertex <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>(M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Exactly <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math> edges that form a spanning tree are required.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>BD</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>DC</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>DE</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>DF</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>OR</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>19</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>21</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>22</mn></math> seen in that order&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>M1A0</strong></em> for diagram of MST.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>attempt to reconnect vertex <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> (one edge is sufficient)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>reconnecting <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>:</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>AE</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mn>22</mn></mfenced></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AF</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mn>23</mn></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>lower bound: <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>19</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>21</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>23</mn></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>127</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> If <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>127</mn></math> seen, unsupported or without the explicit evidence of Prim’s algorithm, award <em><strong>M1A0M1A1A1</strong></em>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22579244","referenceCode":"24M.2.AHL.TZ2.4b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"By deleting A, use Prim’s algorithm starting at B to find a lower bound for the length of the inspector’s journey.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.14—Graph theory","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.16—Tree and cycle algorithms, Chinese postman, travelling salesman"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}